<font face="Verdana" color="#D0B078" size="3"><b>Insights into NPC/Mob AI</b></font> 
<br>
<font face="Verdana" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">Posted: Friday, June 9 by <a href="mailto:delsonora@brellserilis.net">Delsonora</a> @ 10:41 AM EDT<br>
<font face="Verdana" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
Add a <a href="http://www.brellserilis.net/news/talkback/960565273,78406,.html">comment</a> on this article [0 Comments]</font><br>

<br><br><font face="Verdana" size="2"> Now, i didnt know this but Gordon responding to someone's post about a documented bug where a cleric will sit down in a zone and have mobs out of range go hostile (I believe that is the summary of the bug, if i am mistaken i apologize) yielded this interesting response from Gordon into how mobs handle hate lists.<br><br><i>NPCs attack. They attack without warning and provocation. The fact that an NPC somewhere had you on the hatelist, but was too far away to consider chasing you, and was <b>propagating that hatelist</b> to new NPCs that spawned who *were* in range to chace after you, is a design issue that players just have to deal with at the moment. Everything that is happening in this case is *intended*, it just *sucks*. Sometimes things that "suck" are described as bugs, but aren't bugs in sense of something that we can fix readily, or that we would give a rez for.<br><br>-Gordon</i></font><br><br><br>
