<font face="Verdana" color="#D0B078" size="3"><b>Holy Smokes!! Must READ</b></font> 
<br>
<font face="Verdana" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">Posted: Tuesday, May 9 by <a href="mailto:delsonora@brellserilis.net">Delsonora</a> @ 12:14 PM EDT<br>
<font face="Verdana" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
Add a <a href="http://www.brellserilis.net/news/talkback/957892452,15438,.html">comment</a> on this article [0 Comments]</font><br>

<br><br><font face="Verdana" size="2"> As we are sure many people are aware, there are guards that exist specifically for the purpose of giving new characters a place to run in order to be saved from a certain death. However, as many people have mentioned, these guards are frequently either dead, or engaged by players choosing to hunt them. This makes things very frustrating for newer players, and with the large influx of new players due to the release of EverQuest: The Ruins of Kunark, we've decided to make a change.<br>Though we do not have a problem with players choosing to hunt guards, the newbie guards themselves, specifically the ones at the gates of cities and in the vicinity of newbie zones, need to remain alive under most circumstances. To that end, tomorrow morning we will be buffing up these newbie-protecting guards, making them immune to magic, and giving them some pretty good healing properties in order to make them less attractive to people hunting them.<br><br>In addition, though we will leave the guards inside cities as-is from the perspective of power, we've also found a problem with the respawn rate. Currently they are typically on six-minute timers, making them spawn much faster than an equivalent NPC would in a dungeon. We will be normalizing the respawn time of guards inside cities to bring them in line with dungeon NPCs. <br><br>-Gordon<br></font><br><br><br>
<a name="newsitem957880543,77785,"></a>
