<font face="Verdana" color="#D0B078" size="3"><b>Abashi responds to Del!!</b></font> 
<br>
<font face="Verdana" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">Posted: Wednesday, May 3 by <a href="mailto:delsonora@brellserilis.net">Delsonora</a> @ 9:43 AM EDT<br>
<font face="Verdana" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
Add a <a href="http://www.brellserilis.net/news/talkback/957365030,10566,.html">comment</a> on this article [0 Comments]</font><br>

<br><br><font face="Verdana" size="2"> I posted this on the EQ Board. Didnt think anyone would even see it but Gordon responded =) Anyway, i think his response is valid. Check it out hehe.<br><br>>>>Would it be possible, or difficult, to implement a way for members of a class to talk to each other over a channel (like guildtalk). I think this could be useful for players communicating with others in their class regarding quests, strategy, exchange of research components, etc. e.g. /class Anyone have any information on the spell call of bones?<br><br>Blanket communication channels tend to reduce the sense of community in game, rather than enhance it. Instead of dealing with a specific person, and forming a relationship with them, it ends up pretty cold. This is somewhat apparent with zone-wide communications such as /shout and /ooc, however it's not as bad as a server-wide mechanism would be. In addition to this, there are some technical issues surrounding this idea (e.g. the number of additional packets to broadcast) which make the idea unattractive.<br><br>-Gordon<br><br></font><br><br><br>
